You have a variable scope issue here: the `$post` object won&#39;t be available in your function unless you use the `global` keyword.

```
add_action( &#39;wp_head&#39;, function() {
   global $post;

   if ($post-&gt;ID == 7407 || $post-&gt;ID == 7640 || $post-&gt;ID == 7660) {
        echo &#39;&lt;meta name=&quot;robots&quot; content=&quot;noindex, nofollow&quot;&gt;&#39;;
    }
} );
```

However, the `$post` object isn&#39;t always available: it only gets set when actually viewing a `post`, `page`, or a custom post type. If you try to use this code as is it&#39;ll throw some PHP warnings when `$post` isn&#39;t set so it might be a better idea to use the [is_page()](https://developer.wordpress.org/reference/functions/is_page/) function instead because the function does this check for you automatically:

```
add_action( &#39;wp_head&#39;, function() {
   if (is_page(7407) || is_page(7640) || is_page(7660)) {
        echo &#39;&lt;meta name=&quot;robots&quot; content=&quot;noindex, nofollow&quot;&gt;&#39;;
    }
} );
```

